fleck (M. F. fleche), a fletch. This word

seems to have denoted a particular part of an arrow. Thus we have ‘duas sagittas barbatas sine fleck’ (pp. 94, 95), which are also described as ⁴ due sagitte fracte! The fletch would be the wooden part of the arrow, on which the metal head and the feathers were fixed. In the Huntinqdon Feet of Fines, File 11, No. 220, we have the words ‘ una fieccha pennata.' Perhaps a dart with- out a metal head was called a fletch. The passages in which arrows are mentioned in this volume are collected together under the word walisoa below.
